cs.DC, cs.DS, cs.OS, cs.AR, cs.PL 

This paper deals with concurrent data structures and algorithms, specifically in the context of non-volatile memory. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing). The paper also discusses the design of efficient data structures, which suggests that it could belong to cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). The use of persistent memory and recovery from system crashes could also place it in cs.OS (Operating Systems). The paper mentions the use of CAS (Compare-and-Swap) operations, which are commonly used in hardware design, suggesting that it could belong to cs.AR (Hardware Architecture). Finally, the paper discusses the transformation of concurrent programs, which could place it in cs.PL (Programming Languages).
